<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO ARTHUR RE CYCLES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  9 20:36:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur, you lost me on this one. Probably just as well.<br><br>
34 years and 5 days ago I was celebrating my 18th birthday (dob 8-4-45). I went down to Local Board #125 and registered for the Draft. I was totally gung-ho and patriotic. In was 1963, I had just graduated high school, I had a job at a McDonalds, A hot 56 chevy and a hotter girlfriend. I surfed by day, and parked by night, and knew I was going to college in a month or two.  Somehow, over the next couple of years the world that I knew changed. It has never stopped changing since.  When I was 18 I was immortal, unstoppable, unbeatable, the center of my universe. <br><br>
By the time I was 20 or 21 I knew that was not true. I guess that is what is ment by growing up. I knew the world was a potentially dangerous place, and it could kill me if I was not carefull. I had lost more than must my virginity.<br><br>
Now I have a son who is 18, who thinks he is the center of his world, unstoppable, unbeatable, with a hot car and a hot girl friend. Like father, like son. The difference is that he does not have a draft card burning in his wallet.  How is this for symbolic imagery, most of the guys I knew carried a condom (for luck) and a draft card (by law) in their wallets. One to stop the start of life, the other to cause the end of life too, but in quite a different manner. Sweet irony.<br><br>
What has my life taught me?  Unlike what I think Art is saying, I have come to terms with the fact that I can change, and often do. I have learned that it is ok to be wrong, and to &quot;wisen up&quot;. I have learned that no war is a good war. I have learned that what they taught me in political science and govenment, high school or college, was a crock. I have learned that my government is my biggest enemy.<br><br>
I pray my son, and my younger daughter will never know the feeling of waking up with a draft card, a death warrant, in their pocket, before they have reached maturity.  A washing machine has cycles, as Art points out, but so does life. So does death. So does each generation.  If we can bridge differences, in this site, between warriors who faught, and &quot;warriors&quot; who resisted (easy Ed), of governments that lied, and liars that governed, and that our children will never have to creep down a jungle trail looking for trip wires, or down agency hallways looking for paperwork boobytraps, then we have all come together, what's left of our generation that is, and given the next generations the benefits of our learning.<br><br>
Art, I guess turning 52 has me stuck in my melincholy (sp?) cyclic, sorry bout that.  It has been a long and introspective week. A week where I feel more like reaching out that striking out.  I am sure you have had those too. Actually, they are kinda peaceful and nice.<br><br>
doc spatz
